_exec_summary.SummaryText:
 this is a two-phase release of both liquid chlorine and gaseous chlorine. This scenario releases 1,500 pounds of chlorine gas in fifteen minutes. The distance to the endpoint was estimated to be 0.20 miles from the chlorination facility assuming a wind speed of 6.7 miles/hour and an atmospheric rating of "Class D". The endpoint determination includes enclosure of the cylinder within the storage room. The potential population affected by the alternate release scenario was estimated to be 200 persons.

Actuation of the Chlorine Gas Detectors is considered to be an active mitigation measure. Additionally, the chlorine gas piping is vacuum tubing connected directly to the chlorine cylinders. A loss of vacuum in the tubing immediately stops the flow of chlorine gas from the cylinders and virtually eliminates the possibility of a chlorine release due a piping leak. The Salem Water Treatment Plant is equipped with a Chlorine Gas Scrubber, which is also considered to be an active mitigation measure.

The Salem Water Treatment Plant RMP has the key elements listed below. These elements are aimed at preventing a chlorine release from the chlorination system.

* High level of operator training and maintenance training;
* An established preventive maintenance program;
* Implementation of an audit and inspection program;
* Use of effective written operating procedures;
* Implementation of an employee participation program;
* Use of emergency air supply and cylinder leak kits;
* Use a of chlorine gas scrubber;
* Performance of process hazard analysis and compliance auditing procedures;
* Use of process alarms and emergency shut down procedures;
* Annual chlorine safety training by the chlorine supplier; and 
* Quarterly demonstration and practice sessions using emergency air supply.

No accidental releases of chlorine gas have occurred at the Salem Water Treatment Plant in the past five years. 

An emergency response plan is established and is coordinated with the City of Salem
